library(readr)

Read in noaa_fisheries.csv data. data/filename: indicates file location. here function also does this, but makes it less complicated

us_landings <- read_csv(here("data", "noaa_fisheries.csv"))
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Year = col_double(),
##   State = col_character(),
##   `AFS Name` = col_character(),
##   `Landings (pounds)` = col_double(),
##   `Dollars (USD)` = col_character()
## )

Now make a tidy version of the data frame: pipe shortcut: command, shift, m

landings_tidy <- us_landings %>% 
  clean_names() %>%  #janitor package, makes headings into snakecase (compatible with R) 
  mutate(state=str_to_lower(state), afs_name=str_to_lower(afs_name)) %>% #reformat the state & afs_name columns to be lower case (creates a new column & replaces existing column)
  mutate(dollars_num = parse_number(dollars_usd))
#parse number pulls the numeric portion of a dataset if it's paired with a symbol or letter; creates new column with the numeric portion only

Lets get some info for salmon:

salmon_landings <- landings_tidy %>%
  mutate(afs_clean = str_remove(afs_name, pattern = "aggregate")) %>% #remove word aggregate from afs_name
  filter(str_detect(afs_clean, pattern = "salmon"))  %>% # keep any row where the word salmon appears 
  separate(afs_clean, into = c("group", "species"), sep = ",") #puts salmon & type separated by comma into new columns called group and species

Find some grouped summary data: Find annual total US landings and dollar value (summed across all states) for each type of salmon using group_by() + summarize()

salmon_summary <- salmon_landings %>% 
  group_by(year, species) %>% 
  summarize(tot_landings = sum(landings_pounds), tot_value = sum(dollars_num)) #creates summary table for indicated variables

Make a graph!

salmonlandingsgraph <- ggplot(data = salmon_summary, aes(x= year, y= tot_landings)) + 
  geom_line(aes(color=species)) +
  theme_classic()

salmonlandingsgraph
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

Export graph with ggsave. ggsave helps save a graph by exporting it to a specific file.

ggsave(plot = salmonlandingsgraph, here("figures", "us_salmon_apw.jpg"), height = 5, width = 8) # can adjust size of image
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

salmon_first5 <- salmon_summary %>% 
  head(5)
